<HL> The Journal's Daniel Akst Wins a Journalism Award </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> DJ </CO>
<IN> PUB </IN>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Daniel Akst, a reporter in The Wall Street Journal's Los Angeles bureau, won a Hancock award for Excellence in Business and Financial Journalism. 

   Mr. Akst, 32 years old, won an award in the category of newspapers with more than 300,000 circulation for "Fallen Star," a story of the rise and fall of ZZZZ Best Co. and the alleged deceptions of the carpet-cleaning company's founder, Barry Minkow. 

   Mr. Akst joined the Journal in June 1987. 

   The award is sponsored by John Hancock Financial Services, Boston, in cooperation with Fordham University Graduate School of Business Administration, New York. 

   The Wall Street Journal is published by Dow Jones &amp; Co., which also publishes Barron's magazine and other periodicals, electronic business information services and community newspapers. 
It also owns 56% of Telerate Inc., which provides computerized financial information on global markets. 

</TEXT>
